      <hedline>
        <hl1>Joint Decisions</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Crystal J Gips letter comments on Rosalyn Weinman's July 15 Op-Ed article on negotiations between parents' groups and broadcast industry that led to revised ratings system (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I applaud NBC's recognition (Op-Ed, July 15) that determining the appropriateness of television content for one's child is part of the difficult role of parenting.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I applaud NBC's recognition (Op-Ed, July 15) that determining the appropriateness of television content for one's child is part of the difficult role of parenting.</p>
        <p>In addition, joining one's child in selecting and assessing programs may be the most effective way of teaching children to make wise viewing selections for themselves, for ultimately they must act on their own.</p>
        <p>Helping children learn to select programs is not entirely different from helping them learn to make good choices of, say, friends or food. We must help children learn to value their  physical, psychological and intellectual health.</p>
        <p>CRYSTAL J. GIPS  Northridge, Calif., July 16, 1997</p>
        <p>The writer is associate dean of the college of education at California State University, Northridge.</p>
        <p>TV Ratings Deal Didn't Involve 'Arm-Twisting'</p>
      </block>
